Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Peel and grate the @ginger{1/2}(peeled and grated). Trim and halve the @pak choi{2}(trimmed and halved lengthways) then thinly slice widthways. Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}(trimmed and thinly sliced).

Bring a #saucepan{} of water up to the boil with a @salt{pinch} for the noodles. When boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{2} and cook for ~{4%minutes}. Drain in a #sieve{} and drizzle with @oil{} to prevent them from sticking together. Meanwhile, heat a large #frying pan{} over medium heat (no oil!) and add the @sesame seeds{15}. Cook, stirring regularly, until golden, ~{2-3%minutes} (no oil!). 

> Watch it like a hawk as it can burn easily.

Transfer to a #small bowl{} but don't wash the pan.

Drizzle some @oil{} into the now empty pan over high heat. Once hot, add the @British pork mince{240%g} and @star anise{1/2}, break up the pork with a #wooden spoon{} as it cooks. Cook until the pork is browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Add the bok choy, ginger, garlic and half the spring onion and stir-fry for ~{2%minutes}. 

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Add the @Sriracha sauce{2}, @soy sauce{50%ml} and @Pad Thai paste{50%g} to the pork with the @water{150%ml}, mix well and simmer for ~{2-4%minutes}.

> Tip: add a little less sriracha if you don't like it too spicy.
> IMPORTANT: The pork is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle. Don't forget to remove the star anise!

Add the cooked noodles to the pan and combine everything together well. Heat through making sure everything is piping hot. Taste and add @salt or @pepper if needed.

Divide between #bowls{} and scatter over the remaining spring onion and sesame seeds. Enjoy!